title: For Sale:  USFA Rodeo
postcontent: USFA Cowboy Gun! A “almost new” USFA RodeoThis is a USFA (United States Firearms Manufacturing) Rodeo model SAA Colt .38 special revolver, with a 5 ½” barrel. This gun looks as if it has seen slight use. It is rendered in USFA’s Rodeo Matte Blue finish and presentation and checkered US black synthetic composite grips. This model is not just for looks or occasional use but was also designed to be used by Cowboy Action Shooting (SASS) enthusiasts in shooting competitions. Its Matte Blue finish reduces sun glare that a polished finish throws off and the checkered grips help the shooter maintain a solid non-slip grip while handling the gun. This gun is like new in box and was made by USFA, which is now out of business. In the opinion of many collectors, writer/reviewers, and enthusiasts, these  reproduction single action revolvers made by USFA are the acknowledged “best in class” of the Colt style reproduction manufacturers, including Colt itself, as well as Uberti and other high end repro manufacturers. USFA SAA revolvers are celebrated for their unparalleled adherence to original model 1873 and later model specs, exceeding even first generation Colt originals for quality and detail. In addition, this revolver has been "slicked up" by Long Hunter Shooting Supply making an already excellent pistol even better. One of two available with consecutive serial numbers.

title: For Sale:  USFA RODEO
postcontent: This is a USFA (United States Firearms Manufacturing) Rodeo model SAA Colt .38 special revolver, with a 5 ½” barrel. This gun looks as if it has seen slight use. It is rendered in USFA’s Rodeo Matte Blue finish and presentation and checkered US black synthetic composite grips. This model is not just for looks or occasional use but was also designed to be used by Cowboy Action Shooting (SASS) enthusiasts in shooting competitions. Its Matte Blue finish reduces sun glare that a polished finish throws off and the checkered grips help the shooter maintain a solid non-slip grip while handling the gun. This gun is like new in box and was made by USFA, which is now out of business. In the opinion of many collectors, writer/reviewers, and enthusiasts, these  reproduction single action revolvers made by USFA are the acknowledged “best in class” of the Colt style reproduction manufacturers, including Colt itself, as well as Uberti and other high end repro manufacturers. USFA SAA revolvers are celebrated for their unparalleled adherence to original model 1873 and later model specs, exceeding even first generation Colt originals for quality and detail. In addition, this revolver has been "slicked up" by Long Hunter Shooting Supply making an already excellent pistol even better. Also has the low profile hammer for faster target acquisition. One of two available with consecutive serial numbers.

postcontent: https://www.bugoutguns.com/ProductDetails.asp?ProductCode=BF03111COffered for sale is a RANDALL 1911 MODEL GENERAL CURTIS E LEMAY .45 ACP semi automatic pistol. Made out of aircraft grade stainless steel with wooden grip plates. In very good condition with minimal exterior signs of use and a bright and clean bore.*SERIAL #: BF03111C - ONLY 361 GENERAL CURTIS E. LEMAY MODELS WERE MANUFACTURED AND THIS ONE WAS ONE OF HE LAST ONES MANUFACTURED WITH SERIAL # BF03114C BEING THE LAST.THE CURTIS E. LeMAY 4-STAR PISTOLS In 1984, Randall expanded its line with the introduction of a true compact .45 auto, which was designed by Air Force General Curtis E. LeMay. Among his many accomplishments, LeMay had been responsible for establishing the Air Force’s Marksmanship Training Unit. When LeMay created his pistol design, he intended it to be used by members of the Strategic Air Force Command. The general initially tried to have the diminutive .45 produced by Colt. But, that never occurred. As it happened, Art Hanke, who was the head of manufacturing and engineering for Randall, was a personal friend of General LeMay. It was through this liaison that Randall Firearms Company came to produce the LeMay model line of pistols. First of the LeMay pistols was the A311. It sported a 4.25-inch, 10 groove barrel. The slide had a round top and a fixed rear sight. The handle and magazine were shortened by a half-inch, limiting the magazine to six rounds. Overall weight was 35 ounces. Exclusive to the LeMay models were factory-squared trigger guards. In all, 361 of the Model A311 pistols were made in a serial number range of RF02011C through RF03114C. The first A311 was made on March 1, 1984, and production of that model ended on October 25, 1984.

title: For Sale:  Saiga 223 - Russian 5.56mm AK!
postcontent:
Hi, I originally wrote this ad for someone like myself (someone who has done their research and has figured out what they want) however, most of the people interested in this rifle haven't got a clue what makes it so special, so here it is, complete with a lesson in firearms history:

70 years ago, Kalashnikov designed an incredibly reliable semi-automatic rifle, the AK-47. However, the 7.62x39mm cartridge that the AK used wasn't very accurate except at really short range, due to having shitty ballistics.

Meanwhile, over here in the West, we standardized on a rifle design (AR/M-16) that's far less reliable out in the field (it's fine if it's kept clean) but which fires ammunition that's far more accurate, the 5.56x45mm NATO round. 

Logically, the best "survivial rifle" would be one that offers the reliability of the AK yet fires the far more accurate (and likely far more readily available, in a SHTF scenario) NATO round. Sure enough, the Israelis figured out the same thing over fifty years ago, when they began designing the Gailil, which is an AK that shoots NATO 5.56mm ammo.

More recently, the Kalashnikov Company - known as IZHMASH - began exporting genuine Russian AK's under the brand name "Saiga" and several of these Saigas are shipped in western calibers, including 5.56mm.

So... about this Saiga 223: they should've called it the "Saiga 556" because it can safely fire 5.56mm ammo (most civilian .223 rifles cannot - however, 5.56mm "military grade" rifles like the AR and this Saiga 223 can fire either type).

What most people do with these Saigas, since they were imported in a "sporterized" setup (to get around the ban on importing foreign "assault weapons") is upgrade a few parts with American-made aftermarket parts, thus lowering the number of foreign parts to ten or less. When this is done, your Saiga is no longer considered a "foreign assault weapon" under Federal guidelines and you can now use high-capacity magazines, add a pistol grip and/or folding stock, etc, etc. By the way, these guidelines are known as "922R" and there's more on all this here, as well as reasons why converting is a good idea:

http://forum.saiga-12.com/index.php?/topic/39651-why-should-you-convert-your-saiga/ 

Here in Colorado, the ban on high-capacity magazines means you may not possess rifle magazines in excess of 15 rounds' capacity unless you're grandfathered (i.e. you already owned them before the ban went into effect). One of the many awesome things about the Saiga 223 is that there are several ways of modifying it to take AR magazines! This means if you already legally possess AR-type mags, the Saiga can legally use them! If you don't have some grandfathered AR mags, the best price I've found so far for Colorado-legal 15-round magazines is here:

hhttp://www.saigastock.com/surefire-saiga-223-15-round-magazine-p-6507.html

NOTE: serious Saiga buyers will strip the gun down, media-blast all the parts and Duracote them (an ultra-durable, impact-resistant coating kind of like spray-on bedliner). Therefore, a serious buyer is not going to care about the cheap finish that the Russians give these guns, or the crappy, lightweight plastic "furniture" they come with (stock and forearm), since all that's going to be replaced anyhow. There's a lot of useful information on the Internet; here's the main Saiga 223 site:

http://forum.saiga-12.com/index.php?/forum/22-saiga-223/

Here are a bunch of online stores for Saiga parts and accessories:

centerfiresystems.com
mississippiautoarms.com
www.carolinashooterssupply.com
dinzagarms.com

These guys sell a magazine adapter:

http://www.canisdesigngroup.com/m4-magazine-adapter-for-ak.html

These guys specialize in performing the conversion for you, if you don't want to do it yourself (they also make it compatible with AR mags):

http://www.definitivearms.com/main-pages/main_page.html

This particular Saiga 223 has had less than a hundred rounds through it and is in perfect condition functionally. However the cheap Russian finish looks a little crappy (I tried polishing it up a little with a green plastic scrubby and that was not a good idea) and could use a little re-bluing... or else just give it a proper conversion with Duracote.

The original factory ten-round magazine and toolkit are included.

I will only sell in-state (I don't have the time nor the interest in dealing with shipping, sorry). 

A transfer will need to be performed by a licensed dealer at buyer's expense.

$495 firm; no trades.

Thanks for your interest!
